In [2]:
function Lagrange(xsf, ysf, x)
    P = 0
    ln = size(xsf)[1]
    for i in 1:ln
        L = 1
        for j in 1:ln
            if i != j
                L *= (x - xsf[j])/(xsf[i] - xsf[j])
            end
        end
        P += (ysf[i] * L)
    end
    return P
end

Zadanie 2¶

In [5]:
function NewtonInterpolation(xsf, ysf)
    T = Float64[]
    n= size(xsf)[1]
    for a in 1:n
        push!(T, ysf[a])
        for i in 1:a-1
            numerator = T[end] - T[end-a+1]
            denominator = xsf[a] - xsf[a-i]
            push!(T, numerator/denominator)
        end
    end
    newt = Float64[]
    k = 0
    for i in 1:n
        k = k + i
        push!(newt, T[k])
    end
    return newt
end
Out[5]:
NewtonInterpolation (generic function with 1 method)
In [6]:
function Newton(newt, xsf, x)
    n = size(xsf)[1]
    b = newt[n]
    for i = 1:n-1
        b = newt[n-i] + b*(x-xsf[n-i])
    end
    return b
end
Out[6]:
Newton (generic function with 1 method)

df = DataFrame(Alg = String[], Nodes = Int[], Time = Float64[])
for length = 10:50:500
    for i = 1:11
        width = 10/length
        xs = 0:width:10
        ys = [rand() for x in xs]
        test = 0:0.01:10
        lagr, time = @timed [Lagrange(xs, ys, x) for x in test]
        if i > 1
            push!(df, ("Lagrange", length, time))
        end
    end
end

for length = 100:500:5000
    for i = 1:11
        width = 10/length
        xs = 0:width:10
        ys = [rand() for x in xs]
        test = 0:0.01:10
        newt1, time1 = @timed NewtonInterpolation(xs, ys)
        newt2, time2 = @timed [Newton(xs, ys, x) for x in test]
        time = time1 + time2 
        if i > 1
            push!(df, ("Newton", length, time))
            push!(df, ("Newton1", length, time1))
            push!(df, ("Newton2", length, time2))
        end
    end
end

Zadanie 5¶

In [21]:
function Neville(xsf,ysf,x)
    n = size(xsf)[1]
    t = zeros(Float64,n,n)
    for i in 1:n
        t[i,1] = ysf[i]
    end
    for i=2:n
        for k=i:n
            t[k,i] = ((x-xsf[k]) * t[k-1, i-1] - (x-xsf[k-i+1]) * t[k, i-1]) / (xsf[k-i+1]-xsf[k])
        end
    end
    return t[n,n]
end


xsf = 0:1:10
ysf = [rand() for x in xsf]
tests = [1, 1.5, 2.33, 4.75, 5.4, 6.8, 7.35, 9.9]
df3 = DataFrame(Neville = Float64[], Lagrange = Float64[], Różnica = Float64[])
for p in tests
    push!(df3, (Neville(xsf,ysf,p), Lagrange(xsf,ysf,p), abs(Neville(xsf,ysf,p) - Lagrange(xsf,ysf,p))))
end
print(df3)

xs = 1:5
ys = [rand() for x in xs]
xsf = 1:0.01:5
scatter(xs, ys, label="Punkty")
f1 = interpolate(ys, BSpline(Cubic(Natural(OnCell()))))
ysf1=[f1(x) for x in xsf]
plot!(xsf, ysf1, label="Interpolacja sześcienna", title="Porównanie dla 5 węzłów")
f2 = LinearInterpolation(xs, ys)
ysf2=[f2(x) for x in xsf]
plot!(xsf, ysf2, label="Interpolacja liniowa")
f3 = NewtonInterpolation(xs, ys)

plot!(xsf, ysf3, label="Interpolacja metodą Newtona")

W przypadku większej liczby węzłów widoczny jest efekt Rungego. Wraz ze wzrostem liczby węzłów zmniejszyła się dokładność wielomianu interpolującego obliczonego metodą Newtona. Największe różnice zauważalne są na końcach przedziałów.
